presenting? a barrier-if I may so call it-to my further progress.  Again I sounded this depth with a stone; but no response came to its fall.  I was in great perplexity, and I had the friendly voice no longer to guide me.  One step more forward would precipitate me into the horrible abyss; and the ledge upon which I stood was so narrow that it was impossible fore me to turn around.  Presently, I thought I could see a cone-like pillar stretching down into the darkness.  The top of it was exactly in the centre of the well and on a level with the ledge upon which I stood.  The surface of the top was perfectly flat, but only just the size of a man's foot.
I thought, "What a pretty fix I am in.  I can't go back, if I would, and it seems impossible to proceed.  The distance across this horrible pit is too great for me to leap, unless I can secure a foothold on that cone, and make two jumps of it.  But then if I should miss the cone, I shall be dashed to pieces in there unknown depths.  Then, again, if I remain where I am I shall starve to death, and that would be worse than being dashed to pieces.  What shall I do?  God help me!  I will try the leap."
I gave the spring?; my foot caught up on the cone, I swayed to and fro for a minute more, each vibration of the body seeming to render it impossible for me to keep my foothold;
